  "prompt": "Is there a Church that doesn't believe in Trinity?",
  "response": "Yes, there are Christian denominations that do not adhere to the doctrine of the Trinity. One of the most well-known non-Trinitarian Christian groups is the Jehovah's Witnesses. They believe in God the Father (Jehovah) as the only true God and consider Jesus Christ to be His son, but not equal to God the Father. Another group is the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church or Mormons), which teaches a belief in God the Father, Jesus Christ, and the Holy Ghost as three distinct entities, rather than a Trinity of one essence.\n\nAdditionally, Oneness Pentecostals reject the traditional doctrine of the Trinity, instead adhering to a belief in the oneness of God, with Jesus Christ as the manifestation of God in the flesh.\n\nUnitarian Christians also typically reject the Trinity, emphasizing the oneness of God and viewing Jesus as a human who was an inspired teacher.\n\nThese perspectives differ from mainstream Christianity, where the doctrine of the Trinity (the belief in one God in three persons: Father, Son, and Holy Spirit) is a foundational tenet.",
